# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: perceptually-uniform-colormaps
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] The **CIELAB color space**, also referred to as ***L*a*b****, is a color space defined by the International Commission on Illumination (abbreviated CIE) in 1976.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] It expresses color as three values: *L** for perceptual lightness and *a** and *b** for the four unique colors of human vision: red, green, blue and yellow.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] CIELAB was intended as a perceptually uniform space, where a given numerical change corresponds to a similar perceived change in color.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] While the LAB space is not truly perceptually uniform, it nevertheless is useful in industry for detecting small differences in color.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] Like the CIEXYZ space it derives from, CIELAB color space is a device-independent, "standard observer" model.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] The colors it defines are not relative to any particular device such as a computer monitor or a printer, but instead relate to the CIE standard observer which is an averaging of the results of color matching experiments under laboratory conditions.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] The CIELAB space is three-dimensional and covers the entire gamut (range) of human color perception.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] It is based on the opponent model of human vision, where red and green form an opponent pair and blue and yellow form an opponent pair.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] This makes CIELAB a Hering opponent color space.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] The nature of the transformations also characterizes it as a chromatic value color space.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] The lightness value, *L** (pronounced "L star"), defines black at 0 and white at 100.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] The *a** axis is relative to the green–red opponent colors, with negative values toward green and positive values toward red.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] The *b** axis represents the blue–yellow opponents, with negative numbers toward blue and positive toward yellow.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] The lightness value, *L** in CIELAB is calculated using the cube root of the relative luminance with an offset near black.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] This results in an *effective* power curve with an exponent of approximately 0.43 which represents the human eye's response to light under daylight (photopic) conditions.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] The *a** and *b** axes are unbounded and depending on the reference white they can easily exceed ±150 to cover the human gamut.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] Nevertheless, software implementations often clamp these values for practical reasons.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] For instance, if integer math is being used it is common to clamp *a** and *b** in the range of −128 to 127.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] CIELAB is calculated relative to a reference white, for which the CIE recommends the use of CIE Standard illuminant D65.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] D65 is used in the vast majority of industries and applications, with the notable exception being the printing industry which uses D50.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] The International Color Consortium largely supports the printing industry and uses D50 with either CIEXYZ or CIELAB in the Profile Connection Space, for v2 and v4 ICC profiles.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] While the intention behind CIELAB was to create a space that was more perceptually uniform than CIEXYZ using only a simple formula, CIELAB is known to lack perceptual uniformity, particularly in the area of blue hues.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] ) plotted within the CIELAB color space.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] The asterisks (*) after *L**, *a*,* and *b** are pronounced *star* and are part of the full name to distinguish *L***a***b** from Hunter's *Lab*, described below.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] Since the *L*a*b** model has three axes, it requires a three-dimensional space to be represented completely.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] Also, because each axis is non-linear, it is not possible to create a two-dimensional chromaticity diagram.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] Additionally, the visual representations shown in the plots of the full CIELAB gamut on this page are an approximation, as it is impossible for a monitor to display the full gamut of LAB colors.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] The nonlinear relations for *L**, *a** and *b** are intended to mimic the nonlinear response of the visual system.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] In order to convert RGB or CMYK values to or from *L*a*b**, the RGB or CMYK data must be linearized relative to light.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] The reference illuminant of the RGB or CMYK data must be known, as well as the RGB primary coordinates or the CMYK printer's reference data in the form of a color lookup table (CLUT).
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] In color managed systems, ICC profiles contains these needed data, which are then used to perform the conversions.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] As mentioned previously, the *L** coordinate nominally ranges from 0 to 100.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] The range of *a** and *b** coordinates is technically unbounded, though it is commonly clamped to the range of −128 to 127 for use with integer code values, though this results in potentially clipping some colors depending on the size of the source color space.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] The gamut's large size and inefficient utilization of the coordinate space means the best practice is to use floating-point values for all three coordinates.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] Unlike the RGB and CMYK color models, CIELAB is designed to approximate human vision.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] The *L** component closely matches human perception of lightness, though it does not take the Helmholtz–Kohlrausch effect into account.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] CIELAB is less uniform in the color axes, but is useful for predicting small differences in color.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] The CIELAB coordinate space contains the entire gamut of human color vision, which exceeds the gamut of sRGB or CMYK.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] In an integer implementation such as TIFF, ICC or Photoshop, the large coordinate space results in substantial data inefficiency due to unused code values.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] Only about 35% of the available coordinate code values are inside the CIELAB gamut with an integer format.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] Using CIELAB in an 8-bit per channel integer format typically results in significant quantization errors.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] Even 16-bit per channel can result in clipping, as the full gamut extends past the bounding coordinate space.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] Ideally, CIELAB should be used with floating-point data to minimize obvious quantization errors.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] CIE standards and documents are copyrighted by the CIE and must be purchased; however, the formulas for CIELAB are available on the CIE website.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] The division of the domain of the f function into two parts was done to prevent an infinite slope at *t* = 0.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] The function f was assumed to be linear below some *t* = *t*0 and was assumed to match the ${\sqrt[{3}]{t}}$ part of the function at *t*0 in both value and slope.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] ) plotted within the CIELCHab color space.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] The "CIELCh" or "CIEHLC" space is a color space based on CIELAB, which uses the polar coordinates *C** (chroma, colorfulness of the color) and *h*° (hue angle, angle of the hue in the CIELAB color wheel) instead of the Cartesian coordinates *a** and *b**.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] The CIELAB lightness L* remains unchanged.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] The LCh (or HLC) color space is not the same as the HSV, HSL or HSB color models, although their values can also be interpreted as a base color, saturation and lightness of a color.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] The HSL values are a polar coordinate transformation of what is technically defined RGB cube color space.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] Further, *H* and *h* are not identical, because HSL space uses as primary colors the three additive primary colors red, green and blue (*H* = 0, 120, 240°).
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] Instead, the LCh system uses the four colors red, yellow, green and blue (*h* = 0, 90, 180, 270°).
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] Regardless the angle *h*, *C* = 0 means the achromatic colors (non saturated), that is, the gray axis.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] The simplified spellings LCh, LCh(ab), LCH, LCH(ab) and HLC are common, but the letter presents a different order.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] HCL color space (Hue-Chroma-Luminance) on the other hand is a commonly used alternative name for the L*C*h(uv) color space, also known as the *cylindrical representation* or *polar CIELUV*.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] This name is commonly used by information visualization practitioners who want to present data without the bias implicit in using varying saturation.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] The name Lch(ab) is sometimes used to differentiate from L*C*h(uv).
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] A related color space, the CIE 1976 *L***u***v** color space (a.k.a.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] CIELUV), preserves the same *L** as *L*a*b** but has a different representation of the chromaticity components.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] CIELAB and CIELUV can also be expressed in cylindrical form (CIELChab and CIELChuv, respectively), with the chromaticity components replaced by correlates of chroma and hue.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] Since the work on CIELAB and CIELUV, the CIE has been incorporating an increasing number of color appearance phenomena into their models and difference equations to better predict human color perception.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] These color appearance models, of which CIELAB is a simple example, culminated with CIECAM02.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] Oklab is built on the same spatial structure and achieves greater perceptual uniformity.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] Hunter Lab (also known as Hunter L,a,b) is a color space defined in 1948 by Richard S.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] It was designed to be computed via simple formulas from the CIEXYZ space, but to be more perceptually uniform.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] Hunter named his coordinates *L*, *a* and *b*.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/cielab-color-space] Hunter Lab was a precursor to CIELAB, created in 1976 by the International Commission on Illumination (CIE), which named the coordinates for CIELAB as *L**, *a**, *b** to distinguish them from Hunter's coordinates.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-mapping] The term *image color transfer* is a bit of a misnomer since most common algorithms transfer both color and shading.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-mapping] There are two types of image color transfer algorithms: those that employ the statistics of the colors of two images, and those that rely on a given pixel correspondence between the images.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-mapping] In a wide-ranging review, Faridul and others identify a third broad category of implementation, namely user-assisted methods.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-mapping] An example of an algorithm that employs the statistical properties of the images is histogram matching.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-mapping] This is a classic algorithm for color transfer, but it can suffer from the problem that it is too precise so that it copies very particular color quirks from the target image, rather than the general color characteristics, giving rise to color artifacts.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-mapping] Newer statistic-based algorithms deal with this problem.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-mapping] An example of such algorithm is one that adjusts the mean and the standard deviation of each of the source image channels to match those of the corresponding reference image channels.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-mapping] This adjustment process is typically performed in the Lαβ or Lab color spaces.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-mapping] A common algorithm for computing the color mapping when the pixel correspondence is given is building the joint-histogram (see also co-occurrence matrix) of the two images and finding the mapping by using dynamic programming based on the joint-histogram values.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-mapping] When the pixel correspondence is not given and the image contents are different (due to different point of view), the statistics of the image corresponding regions can be used as an input to statistics-based algorithms, such as histogram matching.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-mapping] The corresponding regions can be found by detecting the corresponding features.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-mapping] Liu provides a review of image color transfer methods.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-mapping] The review extends into considerations of video color transfer and deep learning methods including Neural style transfer.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-mapping] Color transfer processing can serve two different purposes: one is calibrating the colors of two cameras for further processing using two or more sample images, the second is adjusting the colors of two images for perceptual visual compatibility.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-mapping] Color calibration is an important pre-processing task in computer vision applications.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-mapping] Many applications simultaneously process two or more images and, therefore, need their colors to be calibrated.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-mapping] Examples of such applications are: Image differencing, registration, object recognition, multi-camera tracking, co-segmentation and stereo reconstruction.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-mapping] Other applications of image color transfer have been suggested.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-mapping] These include the co-option of color palettes from recognised sources such as famous paintings and the use as a further alternative to color modification methods commonly found in commercial image processing applications such as ‘posterise’, ‘solarise’ and ‘gradient’.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-mapping] A web application has been made available to explore these possibilities.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-mapping] The use of the terms *source* and *target* in this article reflects the usage in the seminal paper by Reinhard et al.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-mapping] However, others such as Xiao and Ma reverse that usage and indeed it seems more natural to consider that the colors from a *source* image are directed at a *target* image.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-mapping] Adobe use the term *source* for the color reference image in the Photoshop *Match Color* function.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-mapping] Because of this confusion over terminology, some software releases may incorporate incorrect functionality.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-mapping] To minimise further confusion, it may be good practice henceforth to utilise terms such as *input image* or *base image* or *content image* and *color source image* or *color palette image* respectively.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] A **color space** is a specific organization of colors.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] In combination with color profiling supported by various physical devices, it supports reproducible representations of color – whether such representation entails an analog or a digital representation.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] A "color space" is a useful conceptual tool for understanding the color capabilities of a particular device or digital file.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] When trying to reproduce color on another device, color spaces can show whether shadow/highlight detail and color saturation can be retained, and by how much either will be compromised.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] Adding a specific mapping function between a color model and a reference color space establishes within the reference color space a definite "footprint", known as a *gamut*, and for a given color model, this defines a color space.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] For example, Adobe RGB and sRGB are two different absolute color spaces, both based on the RGB color model.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] When defining a color space, the usual reference standard is the CIELAB or CIEXYZ color spaces, which were specifically designed to encompass all colors the average human can see.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] Since "color space" identifies a particular combination of the color model and the mapping function, the word is often used informally to identify a color model.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] However, even though identifying a color space automatically identifies the associated color model, this usage is incorrect in a strict sense.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] For example, although several specific color spaces are based on the RGB color model, there is no such thing as the singular RGB color space.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] In 1802, Thomas Young postulated the existence of three types of photoreceptors (now known as cone cells) in the eye, each of which was sensitive to a particular range of visible light.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] Hermann von Helmholtz developed the Young–Helmholtz theory further in 1850: that the three types of cone photoreceptors could be classified as short-preferring (blue), middle-preferring (green), and long-preferring (red), according to their response to the wavelengths of light striking the retina.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] The relative strengths of the signals detected by the three types of cones are interpreted by the brain as a visible color.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] But it is not clear that they thought of colors as being points in color space.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] The color-space concept was likely due to Hermann Grassmann, who developed it in two stages.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] First, he developed the idea of vector space, which allowed the algebraic representation of geometric concepts in *n*-dimensional space.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] With this conceptual background, in 1853, Grassmann published a theory of how colors mix; it and its three color laws are still taught, as Grassmann's law.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] Colors can be created in printing with color spaces based on the CMYK color model, using the subtractive primary colors of pigment (**c**yan, **m**agenta, **y**ellow, and **k**ey [black]).
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] To create a three-dimensional representation of a given color space, we can assign the amount of magenta color to the representation's X axis, the amount of cyan to its Y axis, and the amount of yellow to its Z axis.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] The resulting 3-D space provides a unique position for every possible color that can be created by combining those three pigments.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] Colors can be created on computer monitors with color spaces based on the RGB color model, using the additive primary colors (red, green, and blue).
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] A three-dimensional representation would assign each of the three colors to the X, Y, and Z axes.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] Colors generated on a given monitor will be limited by the reproduction medium, such as the phosphor (in a CRT monitor) or filters and backlight (LCD monitor).
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] Another way of creating colors on a monitor is with an HSL or HSV color model, based on hue, saturation, brightness (value/lightness).
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] With such a model, the variables are assigned to cylindrical coordinates.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] Many color spaces can be represented as three-dimensional values in this manner, but some have more, or fewer dimensions, and some, such as Pantone, cannot be represented in this way at all.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] Color space conversion is the translation of the representation of a color from one basis to another.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] This typically occurs in the context of converting an image that is represented in one color space to another color space, the goal being to make the translated image look as similar as possible to the original.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] The RGB color model is implemented in different ways, depending on the capabilities of the system used.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] The most common incarnation in general use as of 2021 is the 24-bit implementation, with 8 bits, or 256 discrete levels of color per channel.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] Any color space based on such a 24-bit RGB model is thus limited to a range of 256×256×256 ≈ 16.7 million colors.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] Some implementations use 16 bits per component for 48 bits total, resulting in the same gamut with a larger number of distinct colors.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] This is especially important when working with wide-gamut color spaces (where most of the more common colors are located relatively close together), or when a large number of digital filtering algorithms are used consecutively.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] The same principle applies for any color space based on the same color model, but implemented at different bit depths.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] CIE 1931 XYZ color space was one of the first attempts to produce a color space based on measurements of human color perception (earlier efforts were by James Clerk Maxwell, König & Dieterici, and Abney at Imperial College) and it is the basis for almost all other color spaces.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] The CIERGB color space is a linearly-related companion of CIE XYZ.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] Additional derivatives of CIE XYZ include the CIELUV, CIEUVW, and CIELAB.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] RGB uses additive color mixing, because it describes what kind of *light* needs to be *emitted* to produce a given color.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] RGB stores individual values for red, green and blue.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] RGBA is RGB with an additional channel, alpha, to indicate transparency.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] Common color spaces based on the RGB model include sRGB, Adobe RGB, ProPhoto RGB, scRGB, and CIE RGB.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] CMYK uses subtractive color mixing used in the printing process, because it describes what kind of inks need to be applied so the light *reflected* from the substrate and through the inks produces a given color.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] One starts with a white substrate (canvas, page, etc.), and uses ink to subtract color from white to create an image.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] CMYK stores ink values for cyan, magenta, yellow and black.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] There are many CMYK color spaces for different sets of inks, substrates, and press characteristics (which change the dot gain or transfer function for each ink and thus change the appearance).
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] YIQ was formerly used in NTSC (North America, Japan and elsewhere) television broadcasts for historical reasons.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] This system stores a luma value roughly analogous to (and sometimes incorrectly identified as) luminance, along with two chroma values as approximate representations of the relative amounts of blue and red in the color.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] It is similar to the YUV scheme used in most video capture systems and in PAL (Australia, Europe, except France, which uses SECAM) television, except that the YIQ color space is rotated 33° with respect to the YUV color space and the color axes are swapped.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] The YDbDr scheme used by SECAM television is rotated in another way.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] It is most commonly seen in its digital form, YCbCr, used widely in video and image compression schemes such as MPEG and JPEG.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] xvYCC is an international digital video color space standard published by the IEC (IEC 61966-2-4).
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] It is based on the ITU BT.601 and BT.709 standards but extends the gamut beyond the R/G/B primaries specified in those standards.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] HSV (**h**ue, **s**aturation, **v**alue), also known as HSB (hue, saturation, **b**rightness) is often used by artists because it is often more natural to think about a color in terms of hue and saturation than in terms of additive or subtractive color components.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] HSV is a transformation of an RGB color space, and its components and colorimetry are relative to the RGB color space from which it was derived.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] HSL (**h**ue, **s**aturation, **l**ightness/**l**uminance), also known as HLS or HSI (hue, saturation, **i**ntensity) is quite similar to HSV, with "lightness" replacing "brightness".
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] The difference is that the *brightness* of a pure color is equal to the brightness of white, while the *lightness* of a pure color is equal to the lightness of a medium gray.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] They largely ignored blue light because the added complexity of a 3-component process provided only a marginal increase in fidelity when compared to the jump from monochrome to 2-component color.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] In this article, we concentrate on the second definition.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] CIEXYZ, sRGB, and ICtCp are examples of absolute color spaces, as opposed to a generic RGB color space.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] A non-absolute color space can be made absolute by defining its relationship to absolute colorimetric quantities.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] For instance, if the red, green, and blue colors in a monitor are measured exactly, together with other properties of the monitor, then RGB values on that monitor can be considered as absolute.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] The CIE 1976 L*, a*, b* color space is sometimes referred to as absolute, though it also needs a white point specification to make it so.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] A popular way to make a color space like RGB into an absolute color is to define an ICC profile, which contains the attributes of the RGB.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] This is not the only way to express an absolute color, but it is the standard in many industries.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] RGB colors defined by widely accepted profiles include sRGB and Adobe RGB.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] The process of adding an ICC profile to a graphic or document is sometimes called *tagging* or *embedding*; tagging, therefore, marks the absolute meaning of colors in that graphic or document.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] A color in one absolute color space can be converted into another absolute color space, and back again, in general; however, some color spaces may have gamut limitations, and converting colors that lie outside that gamut will not produce correct results.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] There are also likely to be rounding errors, especially if the popular range of only 256 distinct values per component (8-bit color) is used.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] One part of the definition of an absolute color space is the viewing conditions.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] The same color, viewed under different natural or artificial lighting conditions, will look different.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] Those involved professionally with color matching may use viewing rooms, lit by standardized lighting.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] Occasionally, there are precise rules for converting between non-absolute color spaces.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] For example, HSL and HSV spaces are defined as mappings of RGB.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] Both are non-absolute, but the conversion between them should maintain the same color.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] However, in general, converting between two non-absolute color spaces (for example, RGB to CMYK) or between absolute and non-absolute color spaces (for example, RGB to L*a*b*) is almost a meaningless concept.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] A different method of defining absolute color spaces is familiar to many consumers as the swatch card, used to select paint, fabrics, and the like.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] This is a way of agreeing a color between two parties.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/color-space] A more standardized method of defining absolute colors is the Pantone Matching System, a proprietary system that includes swatch cards and recipes that commercial printers can use to make inks that are a particular color.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/colorfulness] As colorfulness, chroma, and saturation are defined as attributes of perception, they can not be physically measured as such, but they can be quantified in relation to psychometric scales intended to be perceptually even—for example, the chroma scales of the Munsell system.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/colorfulness] On a Munsell hue page, lines of uniform saturation thus tend to radiate from near the black point, while lines of uniform chroma are vertical.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/colorfulness] The naïve definition of saturation does not specify its response function.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/colorfulness] In the CIE XYZ and RGB color spaces, the saturation is defined in terms of additive color mixing, and has the property of being proportional to any scaling centered at white or the white point illuminant.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/colorfulness] However, both color spaces are non-linear in terms of psychovisually perceived color differences.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/colorfulness] It is also possible — and sometimes desirable — to define a saturation-like quantity that is linearized in term of the psychovisual perception.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/colorfulness] In the CIE 1976 LAB and LUV color spaces, the unnormalized **chroma** is the radial component of the cylindrical coordinate CIE LCh (lightness, chroma, hue) representation of the LAB and LUV color spaces, also denoted as CIE LCh(ab) or CIE LCh for short, and CIE LCh(uv).
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/colorfulness] The chroma in the CIE LCh(ab) and CIE LCh(uv) coordinates has the advantage of being more psychovisually linear, yet they are non-linear in terms of linear component color mixing.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/colorfulness] And therefore, chroma in CIE 1976 Lab and LUV color spaces is very much different from the traditional sense of "saturation".
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/colorfulness] Another, psychovisually even more accurate, but also more complex method to obtain or specify the saturation is to use a color appearance model like CIECAM02.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/colorfulness] Here, the **chroma** color appearance parameter might (depending on the color appearance model) be intertwined with e.g. the physical brightness of the illumination or the characteristics of the emitting/reflecting surface, which is more sensible psychovisually.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/colorfulness] The CIECAM02 chroma $C,$ for example, is computed from a lightness J in addition to a naively evaluated color magnitude $t.$ In addition, a colorfulness M parameter exists alongside the chroma $C.$ It is defined as $M=CF_{B}^{0.25},$ where $F_{L}$ is dependent on the viewing condition.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/colorfulness] The saturation of a color is determined by a combination of light intensity and how much it is distributed across the spectrum of different wavelengths.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/colorfulness] The purest (most saturated) color is achieved by using just one wavelength at a high intensity, such as in laser light.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/colorfulness] If the intensity drops, then as a result the saturation drops.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/colorfulness] To desaturate a color of given intensity in a subtractive system (such as watercolor), one can add white, black, gray, or the hue's complement.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/colorfulness] Various correlates of saturation follow.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/colorfulness] The CIE has not formally recommended this equation since CIELAB has no chromaticity diagram, and this definition therefore lacks direct connection with older concepts of saturation.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/colorfulness] Nevertheless, this equation provides a reasonable predictor of saturation, and demonstrates that adjusting the lightness in CIELAB while holding (*a**, *b**) fixed does affect the saturation.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/colorfulness] This definition is inspired by experimental work done with the intention of remedying CIECAM97s's poor performance.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/colorfulness] M is proportional to the chroma $C,$ thus the CIECAM02 definition bears some similarity to the CIELUV definition.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/colorfulness] Saturation is also one of three coordinates in the HSL and HSV color spaces.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/colorfulness] However, in the HSL color space saturation exists independently of lightness.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/colorfulness] That is, both a very light color *and* a very dark color can be heavily saturated in HSL; whereas in the previous definitions—as well as in the HSV color space—colors approaching white all feature low saturation.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/colorfulness] Different color spaces, such as CIELAB or CIELUV may be used, and will yield different results.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] A **rainbow** is an optical phenomenon caused by refraction, internal reflection and dispersion of light in water droplets resulting in a continuous spectrum of light appearing in the sky.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The rainbow takes the form of a multicoloured circular arc.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Rainbows caused by sunlight always appear in the section of sky directly opposite the sun.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Rainbows can be caused by many forms of airborne water.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] These include not only rain, but also mist, spray, and airborne dew.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] However, the observer typically sees only an arc formed by illuminated droplets above the ground, and centred on a line from the Sun to the observer's eye.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] In a primary rainbow, the arc shows red on the outer part and violet on the inner side.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] This rainbow is caused by light being refracted when entering a droplet of water, then reflected inside on the back of the droplet and refracted again when leaving it.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] In a double rainbow, a second arc is seen about 10° outside the primary arc.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Its colours are perceived to be in reverse order, with red on the lower side of the arc.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The Guinness World Records holder of the longest-lasting rainbow observed was 8 hours 58 minutes in the Yangmingshan range of Taipei, Taiwan in November 2017.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Rainbows can be observed whenever there are water drops in the air and sunlight shining from behind the observer at a low altitude angle.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Because of this, rainbows are usually seen in the western sky during the morning and in the eastern sky during the early evening.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The most spectacular rainbow displays happen when half the sky is still dark with raining clouds and the observer is at a spot with clear sky in the direction of the Sun.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The result is a luminous rainbow that contrasts with the darkened background.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] During such good visibility conditions, the larger but fainter secondary rainbow is often visible.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] It appears about 10° outside of the primary rainbow, with the inverse order of colours.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The rainbow effect is also commonly seen near waterfalls or fountains.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] In addition, the effect can be artificially created by dispersing water droplets into the air during a sunny day.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Rarely, a moonbow, lunar rainbow, or nighttime rainbow can be seen on strongly moonlit nights.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] As human visual perception for colour is poor in low light, moonbows are often perceived to be white.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] It is difficult to photograph the complete semicircle of a rainbow in one frame, as this would require an angle of view of 84°.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] For a 35 mm camera, a wide-angle lens with a focal length of 19 mm or less would be required.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Now that software for stitching several images into a panorama is available, images of the entire arc and even secondary arcs can be created fairly easily from a series of overlapping frames.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] From above the Earth such as in an aeroplane, it is sometimes possible to see a rainbow as a full circle.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] This phenomenon can be confused with the glory phenomenon, but a glory is usually much smaller, covering only 5–20°.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The sky inside a primary rainbow is brighter than the sky outside of the bow.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] This is because each raindrop is a sphere, and it scatters light over an entire circular disc in the sky.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The radius of the disc depends on the wavelength of light, with red light being scattered over a larger angle than blue light.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Over most of the disc, scattered light at all wavelengths overlaps, resulting in white light which brightens the sky.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] At the edge, the wavelength dependence of the scattering gives rise to the rainbow.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The light of a primary rainbow arc is 96% polarised tangential to the arc.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The light of the second arc is 90% polarised.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] For colours seen by the human eye, the most commonly cited and remembered sequence is Isaac Newton's sevenfold red, orange, yellow, green, blue, indigo and violet, remembered by the mnemonic *Richard Of York Gave Battle In Vain,* or as the name of a fictional person (Roy G.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The initialism is sometimes referred to in reverse order, as VIBGYOR.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] More modernly, the rainbow is often divided into red, orange, yellow, green, cyan, blue and violet.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The apparent discreteness of main colours is an artefact of human perception and the exact number of main colours is a somewhat arbitrary choice.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Newton, who admitted his eyes were not very critical in distinguishing colours, originally (1672) divided the spectrum into five main colours: red, yellow, green, blue and violet.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Later, he included orange and indigo, giving seven main colours by analogy to the number of notes in a musical scale.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Newton chose to divide the visible spectrum into seven colours out of a belief derived from the beliefs of the ancient Greek sophists, who thought there was a connection between the colours, the musical notes, the known objects in the Solar System, and the days of the week.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Scholars have noted that what Newton regarded at the time as "blue" would today be regarded as cyan, what Newton called "indigo" would today be called blue.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The colour pattern of a rainbow is different from a spectrum, and the colours are less saturated.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] There is spectral smearing in a rainbow since, for any particular wavelength, there is a distribution of exit angles, rather than a single unvarying angle.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] In addition, a rainbow is a blurred version of the bow obtained from a point source, because the disk diameter of the sun (0.5°) cannot be neglected compared to the width of a rainbow (2°).
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The number of colour bands of a rainbow may therefore be different from the number of bands in a spectrum, especially if the droplets are particularly large or small.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Therefore, the number of colours of a rainbow is variable.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] If, however, the word *rainbow* is used inaccurately to mean *spectrum*, it is the number of main colours in the spectrum.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Moreover, rainbows have bands beyond red and violet in the respective near infrared and ultraviolet regions; however, these bands are not visible to humans.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Only near frequencies of these regions to the visible spectrum are included in rainbows, since water and air become increasingly opaque to these frequencies, scattering the light.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The UV band is sometimes visible to cameras using black and white film.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The question of whether everyone sees seven colours in a rainbow is related to the idea of linguistic relativity.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Suggestions have been made that there is universality in the way that a rainbow is perceived.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] However, more recent research suggests that the number of distinct colours observed and what these are called depend on the language that one uses, with people whose language has fewer colour words seeing fewer discrete colour bands.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Light rays enter a raindrop from one direction (typically a straight line from the Sun), reflect off the back of the raindrop, and fan out as they leave the raindrop.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The light leaving the rainbow is spread over a wide angle, with a maximum intensity at the angles 40.89–42°.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] (Note: Between 2 and 100% of the light is reflected at each of the three surfaces encountered, depending on the angle of incidence.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] White light separates into different colours on entering the raindrop due to dispersion, causing red light to be refracted less than blue light.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] When sunlight encounters a raindrop, part of the light is reflected and the rest enters the raindrop.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The light is refracted at the surface of the raindrop.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] When this light hits the back of the raindrop, some of it is reflected off the back.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] When the internally reflected light reaches the surface again, once more some is internally reflected and some is refracted as it exits the drop.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] This angle is independent of the size of the drop, but does depend on its refractive index.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Seawater has a higher refractive index than rain water, so the radius of a "rainbow" in sea spray is smaller than that of a true rainbow.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] This is visible to the naked eye by a misalignment of these bows.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The reason the returning light is most intense at about 42° is that this is a turning point – light hitting the outermost ring of the drop gets returned at less than 42°, as does the light hitting the drop nearer to its centre.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] There is a circular band of light that all gets returned right around 42°.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] If the Sun were a laser emitting parallel, monochromatic rays, then the luminance (brightness) of the bow would tend toward infinity at this angle if interference effects are ignored .
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] But since the Sun's luminance is finite and its rays are not all parallel (it covers about half a degree of the sky), the luminance does not go to infinity.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Furthermore, the amount by which light is refracted depends upon its wavelength, and hence its colour.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Blue light (shorter wavelength) is refracted at a greater angle than red light, but due to the reflection of light rays from the back of the droplet, the blue light emerges from the droplet at a smaller angle to the original incident white light ray than the red light.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Due to this angle, blue is seen on the inside of the arc of the primary rainbow, and red on the outside.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The result of this is not only to give different colours to different parts of the rainbow, but also to diminish the brightness.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The light at the back of the raindrop does not undergo total internal reflection, and most of the light emerges from the back.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] A rainbow does not exist at one particular location.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Many rainbows exist; however, only one can be seen, depending on the particular observer's viewpoint, as droplets of light illuminated by the sun.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] All raindrops refract and reflect the sunlight in the same way, but only the light from some raindrops reaches the observer's eye.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] This light is what constitutes the rainbow for that observer.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The whole system composed by the Sun's rays, the observer's head, and the (spherical) water drops has an axial symmetry around the axis through the observer's head and parallel to the Sun's rays.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The rainbow is curved because the set of all the raindrops that have the right angle between the observer, the drop, and the Sun, lies on a cone pointing at the sun with the observer at the tip.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The base of the cone forms a circle at an angle of 40–42° to the line between the observer's head and their shadow, but 50% or more of the circle is below the horizon, unless the observer is sufficiently far above the earth's surface to see it all, for example, in an aeroplane (see below).
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Alternatively, an observer with the right vantage point may see the full circle in a fountain or waterfall spray.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Conversely, at lower latitudes near midday (specifically, when the sun's elevation exceeds 42 degrees) a rainbow will not be visible against the sky.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] It is possible to determine the perceived angle that the rainbow subtends as follows.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Given a spherical raindrop, and defining the perceived angle of the rainbow as 2*φ*, and the angle of the internal reflection as 2*β*, the angle of incidence of the Sun's rays with respect to the drop's surface normal is 2*β* − *φ*.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] where *n* = 1.333 is the refractive index of water (for green light).
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The rainbow occurs where the angle *φ* has an extremum with respect to the angle *β*, that is, *dφ*/*dβ* = 0.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Solving for *β* yields $\beta _{\text{max}}=\arccos \left({\frac {2{\sqrt {-1+n^{2}}}}{{\sqrt {3}}n}}\right)\approx 40.2^{\circ }.$ Substituting back into the earlier equation for *φ* yields 2*φ*max ≈ 42° as the radius angle of the rainbow.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] For red light (wavelength 750 nm, *n* = 1.330 based on the dispersion relation of water), the radius angle is 42.5°; for blue light (wavelength 350 nm, *n* = 1.343), the radius angle is 40.6°.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] A secondary rainbow, at a greater angle than the primary rainbow, is often visible.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The term **double rainbow** is used when both the primary and secondary rainbows are visible.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] In theory, all rainbows are double rainbows, but since the secondary bow is always fainter than the primary, it may be too weak to spot in practice.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Secondary rainbows are caused by a double reflection of sunlight inside the water droplets.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Technically, the secondary bow is centred on the sun itself, but since its angular size is more than 90° (about 127° for violet to 130° for red), it is seen on the same side of the sky as the primary rainbow, about 10° outside it at an apparent angle of 50–53°.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] As a result of the "inside" of the secondary bow being "up" to the observer, the colours appear reversed compared to those of the primary bow.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The secondary rainbow is fainter than the primary because more light escapes from two reflections compared to one and because the rainbow itself is spread over a greater area of the sky.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Each rainbow reflects white light inside its coloured bands, but that is "down" for the primary and "up" for the secondary.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The dark area of unlit sky lying between the primary and secondary bows is called Alexander's band, after Alexander of Aphrodisias, who first described it.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Unlike a double rainbow that consists of two separate and concentric rainbow arcs, the very rare twinned rainbow appears as two rainbow arcs that split from a single base.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The colours in the second bow, rather than reversing as in a secondary rainbow, appear in the same order as the primary rainbow.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] A "normal" secondary rainbow may be present as well.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Twinned rainbows can look similar to, but should not be confused with supernumerary bands.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The two phenomena may be told apart by their difference in colour profile: supernumerary bands consist of subdued pastel hues (mainly pink, purple and green), while the twinned rainbow shows the same spectrum as a regular rainbow.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The cause of a twinned rainbow is believed to be the combination of different sizes of water drops falling from the sky.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Due to air resistance, raindrops flatten as they fall, and flattening is more prominent in larger water drops.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] When two rain showers with different-sized raindrops combine, they each produce slightly different rainbows that may combine and form a twinned rainbow.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] A numerical ray tracing study showed that a twinned rainbow on a photo could be explained by a mixture of 0.40 and 0.45 mm droplets.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] That small difference in droplet size resulted in a small difference in flattening of the droplet shape, and a large difference in flattening of the rainbow top.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Meanwhile, the even rarer case of a rainbow split into three branches was observed and photographed in nature.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] In theory, every rainbow is a circle, but from the ground, usually only its upper half can be seen.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Since the rainbow's centre is diametrically opposed to the Sun's position in the sky, more of the circle comes into view as the sun approaches the horizon, meaning that the largest section of the circle normally seen is about 50% during sunset or sunrise.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Viewing the rainbow's lower half requires the presence of water droplets *below* the observer's horizon, as well as sunlight that is able to reach them.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] These requirements are not usually met when the viewer is at ground level, either because droplets are absent in the required position or because the landscape behind the observer obstructs the sunlight.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] From a high viewpoint, such as a high building or an aircraft, however, the requirements can be met, and the full-circle rainbow can be seen.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Like a partial rainbow, the circular rainbow can have a secondary bow or supernumerary bows as well.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] It is possible to produce the full circle when standing on the ground, for example by spraying a water mist from a garden hose while facing away from the sun.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Since a rainbow’s apparent position depends on the observer’s location and viewing geometry, each person’s eyes intercept light from different sets of droplets at the characteristic angle.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Because of this, observers at different positions, and each observer's two eyes, never see exactly the same rainbow.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] A human observer actually sees one rainbow in front of each eye.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Since the light falls in parallel from each rainbow, the observer perceives it as one single rainbow at an infinite distance.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] This is also perceived when the rainbow is formed at close range, for example in water mist from a garden hose.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] A circular rainbow should not be confused with the glory, which is much smaller in diameter and is created by different optical processes.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] In the right circumstances, a glory and a (circular) rainbow or fog bow can occur together.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Another atmospheric phenomenon that may be mistaken for a "circular rainbow" is the 22° halo, which is caused by ice crystals rather than liquid water droplets, and is located around the Sun (or Moon), not opposite it.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] In certain circumstances, one or several narrow, faintly coloured bands can be seen bordering the violet edge of a rainbow; i.e., inside the primary bow or, much more rarely, outside the secondary.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] These extra bands are called *supernumerary rainbows* or *supernumerary bands*; together with the rainbow itself, the phenomenon is also known as a *stacker rainbow*.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The supernumerary bows are slightly detached from the main bow, become successively fainter along with their distance from it, and have pastel colours (consisting mainly of pink, purple and green hues) rather than the usual spectrum pattern.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The effect becomes apparent when water droplets are involved that have a diameter of about 1 mm or less; the smaller the droplets are, the broader the supernumerary bands become, and the less saturated their colours.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Due to their origin in small droplets, supernumerary bands tend to be particularly prominent in fogbows.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Supernumerary rainbows cannot be explained using classical geometric optics.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The alternating faint bands are caused by interference between rays of light following slightly different paths with slightly varying lengths within the raindrops.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Some rays are in phase, reinforcing each other through constructive interference, creating a bright band; others are out of phase by up to half a wavelength, cancelling each other out through destructive interference, and creating a gap.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Given the different angles of refraction for rays of different colours, the patterns of interference are slightly different for rays of different colours, so each bright band is differentiated in colour, creating a miniature rainbow.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Supernumerary rainbows are clearest when raindrops are small and of uniform size.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The very existence of supernumerary rainbows was historically a first indication of the wave nature of light, and the first explanation was provided by Thomas Young in 1804.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] When a rainbow appears above a body of water, two complementary mirror bows may be seen below and above the horizon, originating from different light paths.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] A **reflected rainbow** may appear in the water surface below the horizon.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The sunlight is first deflected by the raindrops, and then reflected off the body of water, before reaching the observer.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The reflected rainbow is frequently visible, at least partially, even in small puddles.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] A **reflection rainbow** may be produced where sunlight reflects off a body of water before reaching the raindrops, if the water body is large, quiet over its entire surface, and close to the rain curtain.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The reflection rainbow appears above the horizon.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] It intersects the normal rainbow at the horizon, and its arc reaches higher in the sky, with its centre as high above the horizon as the normal rainbow's centre is below it.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Reflection bows are usually brightest when the sun is low because at that time its light is most strongly reflected from water surfaces.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] As the sun gets lower, the normal and reflection bows are drawn closer together.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Due to the combination of requirements, a reflection rainbow is rarely visible.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Occasionally, a shower may happen at sunrise or sunset, where the shorter wavelengths like blue and green have been scattered and essentially removed from the spectrum.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] In addition to the common primary and secondary rainbows, it is also possible for rainbows of higher orders to form.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The order of a rainbow is determined by the number of light reflections inside the water droplets that create it: One reflection results in the **first-order** or *primary* rainbow; two reflections create the **second-order** or *secondary* rainbow.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] More internal reflections cause bows of higher orders—theoretically unto infinity.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] As more and more light is lost with each internal reflection, however, each subsequent bow becomes progressively dimmer and therefore increasingly difficult to spot.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] An additional challenge in observing the **third-order** (or *tertiary*) and **fourth-order** (*quaternary*) rainbows is their location in the direction of the sun (about 40° and 45° from the sun, respectively), causing them to become drowned in its glare.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] For these reasons, naturally occurring rainbows of an order higher than 2 are rarely visible to the naked eye.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Nevertheless, sightings of the third-order bow in nature have been reported, and in 2011, it was photographed definitively for the first time.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Shortly after, the fourth-order rainbow was photographed as well, and in 2014 the first ever pictures of the **fifth-order** (or *quinary*) rainbow were published.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The quinary rainbow lies partially in the gap between the primary and secondary rainbows and is far fainter than even the secondary.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] In a laboratory setting, it is possible to create bows of much higher orders.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Felix Billet (1808–1882) depicted angular positions up to the 19th-order rainbow, a pattern he called a "rose of rainbows".
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] In the laboratory, it is possible to observe higher-order rainbows by using extremely bright and well collimated light produced by lasers.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Up to the 200th-order rainbow was reported by Ng et al. in 1998 using a similar method, but with an argon ion laser beam.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Tertiary and quaternary rainbows should not be confused with "triple" and "quadruple" rainbows—terms sometimes erroneously used to refer to the (much more common) supernumerary bows and reflection rainbows.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Like most atmospheric optical phenomena, rainbows can be caused by light from the Sun, but also from the Moon.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] In case of the latter, the rainbow is referred to as a **lunar rainbow** or **moonbow**.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] They are much dimmer and rarer than solar rainbows, requiring the Moon to be near-full in order for them to be seen.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] For the same reason, moonbows are often perceived as white and may be thought of as monochrome.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The full spectrum is present; however, the human eye is not normally sensitive enough to see the colours.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Long exposure photographs will sometimes show the colour in this type of rainbow.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Fogbows form in the same way as rainbows, but they are formed by much smaller cloud and fog droplets that diffract light extensively.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] They are almost white with faint reds on the outside and blues inside; often one or more broad supernumerary bands can be discerned inside the inner edge.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The colours are dim because the bow in each colour is very broad and the colours overlap.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Fogbows are commonly seen over water when air in contact with the cooler water is chilled, but they can be found anywhere if the fog is thin enough for the sun to shine through and the sun is fairly bright.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] They are very large—almost as big as a rainbow and much broader.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] They sometimes appear with a glory at the bow's centre.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Fog bows should not be confused with ice halos, which are very common around the world and visible much more often than rainbows (of any order), yet are unrelated to rainbows.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] A sleetbow forms in the same way as a typical rainbow, with the exception that it occurs when light passes through falling sleet (ice pellets) instead of liquid water.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] As light passes through the sleet, the light is refracted, causing the rare phenomenon.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] These have been documented across the United States, with the earliest publicly documented and photographed sleetbow being seen in Richmond, Virginia, on 21 December 2012.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Just like regular rainbows, these can also come in various forms, with a monochrome sleetbow being documented on 7 January 2016 in Valparaiso, Indiana.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The circumzenithal and circumhorizontal arcs are two related optical phenomena similar in appearance to a rainbow, but unlike the latter, their origin lies in light refraction through hexagonal ice crystals rather than liquid water droplets.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] This means that they are not rainbows, but members of the large family of halos.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Both arcs have their red side pointing towards the Sun and their violet part away from it, meaning the circumzenithal arc is red on the bottom, while the circumhorizontal arc is red on top.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The circumhorizontal arc is sometimes referred to by the misnomer "fire rainbow".
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] In order to view it, the Sun or Moon must be at least 58° above the horizon, making it a rare occurrence at higher latitudes.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The circumzenithal arc, visible only at a solar or lunar elevation of less than 32°, is much more common, but often missed since it occurs almost directly overhead.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] It has been suggested that rainbows might exist on Saturn's moon Titan, as it has a wet surface and humid clouds.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The radius of a Titan rainbow would be about 49° instead of 42°, because the fluid in that cold environment is methane instead of water.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Although visible rainbows may be rare due to Titan's hazy skies, infrared rainbows may be more common, but an observer would need infrared night vision goggles to see them.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Droplets (or spheres) composed of materials with different refractive indices than plain water produce rainbows with different radius angles.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Since salt water has a higher refractive index, a sea spray bow does not perfectly align with the ordinary rainbow, if seen at the same spot.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Tiny plastic or glass marbles may be used in road marking as a reflectors to enhance its visibility by drivers at night.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Due to a much higher refractive index, rainbows observed on such marbles have a noticeably smaller radius.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] One can easily reproduce such phenomena by sprinkling liquids of different refractive indices in the air, as illustrated in the photo.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The displacement of the rainbow due to different refractive indices can be pushed to a peculiar limit.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] For a material with a refractive index larger than 2, there is no angle fulfilling the requirements for the first order rainbow.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] For example, the index of refraction of diamond is about 2.4, so diamond spheres would produce rainbows starting from the second order, omitting the first order.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] In general, as the refractive index exceeds a number **n** + 1, where **n** is a natural number, the critical incidence angle for **n** times internally reflected rays escapes the domain $[0,{\frac {\pi }{2}}]$ .
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] This results in a rainbow of the **n**-th order shrinking to the antisolar point and vanishing.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The classical Greek scholar Aristotle was first to devote serious attention to the rainbow.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Fraser, "Despite its many flaws and its appeal to Pythagorean numerology, Aristotle's qualitative explanation showed an inventiveness and relative consistency that was unmatched for centuries.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] 65 AD), the Roman philosopher Seneca the Younger discusses various theories of the formation of rainbows extensively, including those of Aristotle.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] He notices that rainbows appear always opposite to the Sun, that they appear in water sprayed by a rower, in the water spat by a fuller on clothes stretched on pegs or by water sprayed through a small hole in a burst pipe.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] He even speaks of rainbows produced by small rods (virgulae) of glass, anticipating Newton's experiences with prisms.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] He takes into account two theories: one, that the rainbow is produced by the Sun reflecting in each water drop, the other, that it is produced by the Sun reflected in a cloud shaped like a concave mirror; he favours the latter.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] He also discusses other phenomena related to rainbows: the mysterious "virgae" (rods), halos and parhelia.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] According to Hüseyin Gazi Topdemir, the Arab physicist and polymath Ibn al-Haytham attempted to provide a scientific explanation for the rainbow phenomenon.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] In his *Maqala fi al-Hala wa Qaws Quzah* (*On the Rainbow and Halo*), al-Haytham "explained the formation of rainbow as an image, which forms at a concave mirror.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] If the rays of light coming from a farther light source reflect to any point on axis of the concave mirror, they form concentric circles in that point.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] This explanation was repeated by Averroes, and, though incorrect, provided the groundwork for the correct explanations later given by Kamāl al-Dīn al-Fārisī in 1309 and, independently, by Theodoric of Freiberg—both having studied al-Haytham's *Book of Optics*.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] In Song dynasty China (960–1279), a polymath scholar-official named Shen Kuo hypothesised—as Sun Sikong did before him—that rainbows were formed by a phenomenon of sunlight encountering droplets of rain in the air.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] According to Nader El-Bizri, the Persian astronomer, Qutb al-Din al-Shirazi (1236–1311), gave a fairly accurate explanation for the rainbow phenomenon.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] This was elaborated on by his student, Kamāl al-Dīn al-Fārisī (1267–1319), who gave a more mathematically satisfactory explanation of the rainbow.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] As he noted in his *Kitab Tanqih al-Manazir* (*The Revision of the Optics*), al-Farisi used a large, clear vessel of glass in the shape of a sphere, which was filled with water, in order to have an experimental large-scale model of a rain drop.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] He then placed this model within a camera obscura that has a controlled aperture for the introduction of light.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] He projected light onto the sphere and ultimately deduced through several trials and detailed observations of reflections and refractions of light that the colours of the rainbow are phenomena of the decomposition of light.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] In Europe, Ibn al-Haytham's *Book of Optics* was translated into Latin and studied by Robert Grosseteste.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] His work on light was continued by Roger Bacon, who wrote in his *Opus Majus* of 1268 about experiments with light shining through crystals and water droplets showing the colours of the rainbow.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] In addition, Bacon was the first to calculate the angular size of the rainbow.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] He stated that the rainbow summit can not appear higher than 42° above the horizon.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Theodoric of Freiberg is known to have given an accurate theoretical explanation of both the primary and secondary rainbows in 1307.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Descartes' 1637 treatise, *Discourse on Method (Discours de la Méthode),* further advanced this explanation.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Knowing that the size of raindrops did not appear to affect the observed rainbow, he experimented with passing rays of light through a large glass sphere filled with water.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] By measuring the angles that the rays emerged, he concluded that the primary bow was caused by a single internal reflection inside the raindrop and that a secondary bow could be caused by two internal reflections.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] He supported this conclusion with a derivation of the law of refraction (subsequently to, but independently of, Snell) and correctly calculated the angles for both bows.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] His explanation of the colours, however, was based on a mechanical version of the traditional theory that colours were produced by a modification of white light.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Isaac Newton demonstrated that white light was composed of the light of all the colours of the rainbow, which a glass prism could separate into the full spectrum of colours, rejecting the theory that the colours were produced by a modification of white light.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] He also showed that red light is refracted less than blue light, which led to the first scientific explanation of the major features of the rainbow.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Newton's corpuscular theory of light was unable to explain supernumerary rainbows, and a satisfactory explanation was not found until Thomas Young realised that light behaves as a wave under certain conditions, and can interfere with itself.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Young's work was refined in the 1820s by George Biddell Airy, who explained the dependence of the strength of the colours of the rainbow on the size of the water droplets.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Modern physical descriptions of the rainbow are based on Mie scattering, work published by Gustav Mie in 1908.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Advances in computational methods and optical theory continue to lead to a fuller understanding of rainbows.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] For example, Nussenzveig provides a modern overview.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Experiments on the rainbow phenomenon using artificial raindrops, i.e. water-filled spherical flasks, go back at least to Theodoric of Freiberg in the 14th century.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Later, Descartes also studied the phenomenon using a Florence flask.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] A flask experiment known as Florence's rainbow is still often used today as an imposing and intuitively accessible demonstration experiment of the rainbow phenomenon.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] It consists in illuminating (with parallel white light) a water-filled spherical flask through a hole in a screen.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] A rainbow will then appear thrown back / projected on the screen, provided the screen is large enough.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Due to the finite wall thickness and the macroscopic character of the artificial raindrop, several subtle differences exist as compared to the natural phenomenon, including slightly changed rainbow angles and a splitting of the rainbow orders.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] A very similar experiment involves using a cylindrical glass vessel filled with water or a solid transparent cylinder and illuminating it either parallel to the circular base (i.e., light rays remain at a fixed height as they transit the cylinder) or under an angle to the base.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Under these latter conditions, the rainbow angles change relative to the natural phenomenon since the effective index of refraction of water changes (Bravais' index of refraction for inclined rays applies).
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Other experiments use small liquid drops.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Rainbows occur frequently in mythology, and have been used in the arts.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] An early literary occurrence of a rainbow is in the Epic of Gilgamesh, with an appearance after a flood.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] A rainbow also similarly appears in the Book of Genesis as part of the flood account of Noah.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] In Norse mythology, the rainbow bridge Bifröst connects the world of men (Midgard) and the realm of the gods (Asgard).
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Cuchavira was the god of the rainbow for the Muisca in present-day Colombia and when the regular rains on the Bogotá savanna were over the people thanked him, offering gold, snails and small emeralds.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Some forms of Tibetan Buddhism or Dzogchen reference a rainbow body.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The Irish leprechaun's secret hiding place for his pot of gold is usually said to be at the end of the rainbow.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] In Greek mythology, the goddess Iris is the personification of the rainbow, a messenger goddess who, like the rainbow, connects the mortal world with the gods through messages.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] In Albanian folk beliefs the rainbow is regarded as the belt of the goddess Prende, and oral legend has it that anyone who jumps over the rainbow changes their sex.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] In heraldry, the rainbow proper consists of 4 bands of colour (argent, gules, or, and vert) with the ends resting on clouds.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Generalised examples in coat of arms include those of the towns of Regen and Pfreimd, both in Bavaria, Germany; of Bouffémont, France; and of the 69th Infantry Regiment (New York) of the United States Army National Guard.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Rainbow flags have been used for centuries.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] It was a symbol of the Cooperative movement in the German Peasants' War in the 16th century, of peace in Italy, and of LGBT pride and LGBT social movements; the rainbow flag as a symbol of LGBT pride and the June pride month since it was designed by Gilbert Baker in 1978.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] In 1994, Archbishop Desmond Tutu and President Nelson Mandela described newly democratic post-apartheid South Africa as the rainbow nation.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] The rainbow has also been used in technology product logos, including the Apple Computer logo.
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Many political alliances spanning multiple political parties have called themselves a "Rainbow Coalition".
[src:perceptually-uniform-colormaps/rainbow] Pointing at rainbows has been considered a taboo in many cultures.
